Taylor Swift has become a prominent artist across the pop music industry. She is well known for her heartfelt lyricism that resonates with her audience. Her ability to create touching, emotional songs has propelled her to the top of the music industry. In our attempt to explore and recreate her songwriting expertise, we present Tay-I: Taylor Swift Pop Verse Generator. By creating Taylor Swift's verse generator, we hope to reveal the top features of her songwriting process and recognize the underlying patterns and themes that define her style. We also seek to explore recurring themes across her songs, employ natural language processing and machine learning techniques to imitate her style, and analyze the generated verses' similarity to her actual lyrics through sentiment and word frequencies. Understanding the structure and patterns of Taylor Swift's songs provides insight into her growth and offers valuable lessons for aspiring songwriters and researchers through natural language processing. By analyzing her lyrics through various data science techniques, we aim to uncover her songwriting genius and contribute to the the world of music, technology, and creativity. Tay-I represents an innovative approach to studying one of the most influential figures in contemporary pop music.

Data Curation¶

Datasets¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/jarredpriester/taylor-swift-spotify-dataset/data?select=taylor_swift_spotify.csv

This dataset contains quantitative data about Taylor Swift's music from a Spotify API. It provides a numerical summary of Taylor Swift's albums, with a variety of statistics such as acousticness, loudness, energy, popularity, and even more. This allows us to glean insight about Taylor Swift's writing style without too much analysis of the actual lyrical data.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/thespacefreak/taylor-swift-song-lyrics-all-albums/data

This dataset contains qualitative data of Taylor Swift's song lyrics. This contains the actual lyrics in dataset form. Each CSV corresponds to one of Taylor's albums. Each row is a line from a Taylor Swift song from that album, and each line is labeled with its album, track title, and track number. This will help us immensely.

r = 0.7882937378160497

Explanation: Based on the Pearson's correlation coefficient value r = 0.7882937378160497, there is a strong, positive, linear relationship between the loudness and energy of Taylor Swift's songs. Loudness represents the overall loudness of a track, typically ranging from -60 and 0 dB. Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track and are useful for comparing the relative loudness of tracks. Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude has low energy. Perceptual features contributing to energy include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy. The conclusion made from Pearson's correlation coefficient value is that the louder Taylor Swift's songs are, the more energy the songs contain. This makes sense because many of Taylor Swift's music are pop and country songs that includes different background tracks and instruments, which makes the music faster, louder, and more energetic.

Method 2: Using the Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) hypothesis test to analyze Taylor Swift's song popularity over time

In [ ]:
# Create dataframe containing unique release date and mean popularity score of all songs released on that date
popularity_means = df.groupby(df['release_date'])['popularity'].mean().reset_index()

# Create dataframe containing number of songs released on each unique date (reference dataframe)
song_count = df.groupby(df['release_date'])['name'].count().reset_index()

# Assign column names to number of songs dataframe
song_count.columns = ['release_date', 'song count']

# Merge mean popularity dataframe and song count dataframe on release date
df_grouped_dates = pd.merge(popularity_means, song_count, how = 'inner', on = 'release_date')

# Rename merged dataframe columns and sort dataframe by release date (dates in ascending order)
# Crucial for ADF Test to produce accurate results
df_grouped_dates.columns = ['release_date', 'average_popularity_score', 'song count']
df_grouped_dates.sort_values(by = 'release_date', inplace = True)

# Run ADF Test and store results
result = adfuller(df_grouped_dates['average_popularity_score'])

# Assign test-statistic and p_value variables
test_statistic = result[0]
p_value = result[1]
print(f"P-value: {p_value}\n")

# Sort original dataframe by release date for plotting purposes
df.sort_values(by = 'release_date', inplace = True)

# Create strip plot of release date and popularity where each song is a point
sns.stripplot(x = 'release_date', y = 'popularity', data = df, alpha = 0.25)
plt.xticks(rotation=90) # Rotate x-axis date labels
plt.ylim(0, 100)  # Set y-axis bounds

# Set graph and axes titles
plt.title('Strip Plot of Song Popularity over Time')
plt.xlabel('Dates (yyyy-mm-dd)')
plt.ylabel('Popularity Rank')
plt.grid(True)

P-value: 0.11533516836911045

Explanation: The Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) hypothesis test is a statistical hypothesis test used to analyze changes in a statistic over time. More specifically, it is used to see whether a time series data column (statistics corresponding to specific times across a certain range) is non-stationary, meaning that over time the mean and variance of the statistic change. It finds the probability of a feature in the series, called a unit root, being present. The null hypothesis is that there is no unit root and the series is stationary, meaning that the mean and variance of the series does not change over time. In other words, we cannot show there is a statistical relation between time and the statistic in the series. Then, the alternative hypothesis is that there is a unit root and the series is non-stationary, so the mean and variance of the series does change over time and there is likely a statistical relation betwenen time and the statistic in the series. The ADF test is helpful because times do not need to be evenly spaced for the test to be effective, so it helps analyze popularity over time, given that Taylor does not release albums exactly evenly spaced apart from each other.

In this test, we used popularity score, determined by Spotify on a scale from 0-100 with 100 being the most popular, as the statistic we want to analyze over time. To deal with songs released on the same dates, we grouped together songs of the same release date and found the average of their popularity score. This works because the scatterplot clearly displays that there is not an excessive difference between any of the popularity scores of songs released on the same date. We also counted the number of songs released on each day to make sure the counts were large enough for this test to be meaningful, which they were. After sorting the resulting dataframe in ascending order by dates, the ADF test was run and produced a p-value of 0.11533516836911045, which is above our level of significance of 0.05 for the test. This means that we keep the null hypothesis suggesting that we cannot conclude there is a significant change in the distribution of popularity score over time. We also cannot say that the release dates and popularity scores are related. Even though the graph would suggest that popularity was slightly increased for later release dates, the difference is not large enough to confidently conclude that release date actually has a correlation with popularity. This would also explain why the p value is pretty small but not quite small enough to reject the null hypothesis since the trend does not appear clear enough to be fully confident that such a relationship would exist.

Machine Learning Models¶

The main takeaway that we got from our preliminary exploration of the Spotify API dataset was that Taylor Swift does not have one fixed style. The third method tells us that Taylor Swift has employed many different sounds with varying levels of acoustic instrumentation, which correspond to the different genres she has employed across her career, such as pop, trap, country, and folk. The first method shows us that her music has consistently had varying levels of energy and bombast throughout her career. Yet from the second method, we can see that her music has remained consistently popular throughout. Based on this information, we are predicting that what has made Taylor Swift's music stick in the public consciousness is her ability to convey emotion of all forms. So one way we can evaluate the performance of Tay-I is by comparing sentiment analysis scores for Tay-I and Taylor's actual lyrics. As for the models themselves, we have decided to try multiple different models and compare their results to see which can best recapture the spriit of Taylor's writing. The first will be a probabilistic model called a Markov chain, which utilizes only the previous words generated to generate the next few words. Markov models, despite not using classic machine learning techniques, are useful because of their ability to match the training data and relatively low time complexity. However, they are not space-efficient and do not actually "learn" the training data. The other model we will use is a Recurrent Neural Network (RNN), which is frequently used for sequential data, such as language. This model does actually fully learn the training data, but it is hard for simpler RNNs to grasp language features and semantics accurately.

Markov Model Technique¶

Markov Model¶

In [ ]:
class MarkovSongGenerator:
  # Initlalize the model by initializing the local variables.
  def __init__(self, lyrics, order = 2, temperature = 1.0):
    self.order = order
    self.start_tokens = []
    self.transitions = {}
    self.lyrics = set(lyrics) # Store set of unique lyrics
    self.temperature = temperature
    self.preprocess(lyrics)

  # Preprocess all lyrics
  def preprocess(self, lyrics):
    for line in lyrics:
      # Split each line of lyrics into words
      words = line.split()

      # Add start tokens ('order' number of words per line)
      self.start_tokens.append(tuple(words[:self.order]))

      # Create transitions from previous group of words to next
      for i in range(len(words) - self.order):
        prefix = tuple(words[i:i + self.order])
        suffix = words[i + self.order]

        if prefix in self.transitions:
          self.transitions[prefix].append(suffix)
        else:
          self.transitions[prefix] = [suffix]

  def sample_word(self, prefix):
    # Laplatian smoothing- prevent any word from having 0 probability to help
    # ensure every word has a small chance of getting picked, which improves
    # randomness.
    transition_probs = self.transitions.get(prefix, [])
    vocab_size = len(set(transition_probs))
    smoothed_probs = {}
    for word in transition_probs:
      smoothed_probs[word] = (transition_probs.count(word) + 1) / (len(transition_probs) + vocab_size)

    # Temperature-based sampling
    # In temperature-based sampling, we divide the logarithm of each probability
    # by the temperature to adjust their relative scaling before calculating
    # their softmax distribution
    probs = np.array(list(smoothed_probs.values()))
    scaled_probs = np.log(probs) / self.temperature
    exp_probs = np.exp(scaled_probs)
    softmax_probs = exp_probs / np.sum(exp_probs)

    # Sample from softmax distribution
    sampled_word = np.random.choice(list(smoothed_probs.keys()), p = softmax_probs)
    return sampled_word

  def training_data_similarity_score(self, gen_line):
    # Check if verse is similar to any training data lines
    for line in self.lyrics:
      if self.similarity_score(line, gen_line) > 0.4:  # Adjust threshold as needed
        return True

    return False

  def similarity_score(self, line1, line2):
    # Calculate similarity score between two verses (simple approach where
    # we compare common words of two lines over their total number of words
    words1 = set(line1.split())
    words2 = set(line2.split())
    intersection = len(words1.intersection(words2))
    union = len(words1.union(words2))

    if union != 0:
      similarity = intersection / union
    else:
      similarity = 0

    return similarity

  def generate_lyrics(self, length = 20):
    # Select random start token (probabilistic)
    curr_prefix = random.choice(self.start_tokens)
    gen_line = list(curr_prefix)
    generated_line = ""

    # Generate verse
    while len(gen_line) < length:
      if curr_prefix in self.transitions:
        # Generate next words, build the verse, and push the previous word index down
        next_word = self.sample_word(curr_prefix)
        gen_line.append(next_word)
        curr_prefix = tuple(gen_line[-self.order:])
      else:
        break

    generated_line = ' '.join(gen_line)

    # Post-generation: Filter out exact and too-close matches with training data
    if generated_line in self.lyrics or self.training_data_similarity_score(generated_line):
      return self.generate_lyrics(length)  # Retry generation

    return generated_line

The Markov model is a probabilistic model that utilizes features of the training data to make predictions for what the next word in a generated line should be based on the previous couple of words. In this case, we look at the previous 2 words, because order is 2. We obtain start tokens by looking at the first 2 words of every line, and then progressively add the following 2 words in a line until we reach the end into our transitions dictionary. We then randomly generate a starting word and then sample the word we will add from the list of transitions. To sample, we apply Laplacian smoothing to prevent any word from having 0 probability of being picked, and then utilize temperature-based sampling and exponential normalization (also known as softmax) to generate the final probabilities of words being picked. We then randomly choose a word using these probabilities, and append it to our generated word. At some point, we will reach the end of prefixes in the line, and our generation will be done. As you may suspect, this process is very vulnerable to blatantly copying lines from the training data. To assuage this, we regenerate lines if they are direct copies of the training data, and we also reject any lines that share over 40% of their words with a line from the training data. In this way, our generated lines are based on the training data while maintaining some semblance of uniqueness.

For the generator, we first extract just the lyrics from the lyrics dataframe. We create an instance of the Markov song generator, and then we generate lines. Each line is separated by a \n, and each verse is separated by another \n. In total, we have 5 verses of 10 lines each being generated, and stored in the result string.

Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) Technique¶

RNN¶

# Class not needed since model is relatively simple
# Create a tokenizer for the lyricss
tokenizer = Tokenizer()
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(lyrics)
total_words = len(tokenizer.word_index) + 1

# Create input sequences for the model by tokenizing the lyrics and putting
# the results in a list
input_sequences = []
for line in lyrics:
    token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([line])[0]
    for i in range(1, len(token_list)):
        n_gram_sequence = token_list[:i+1]
        input_sequences.append(n_gram_sequence)

# Pad the input sequences so they maintain similar size in the model
max_sequence_len = max([len(x) for x in input_sequences])
input_sequences = np.array(pad_sequences(input_sequences, maxlen=max_sequence_len, padding='pre'))

# Create predictors and label
predictors, label = input_sequences[:,:-1],input_sequences[:,-1]

# Convert label to one-hot encoding
label = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(label, num_classes=total_words)

# Define the RNN model- Sequential for RNN
# Embedding = Split indices into 100 vectors
# Bidirectional LSTM- where the learning actually happens
# Dense- Fully connected layer that uses softmax to produce probabilities
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Embedding(total_words, 100, input_length=max_sequence_len-1),
    tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(150)),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(total_words, activation='softmax')
])
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model
model.fit(predictors, label, epochs=50, verbose=1)

This is an RNN model. First, we create a tokenizer for Taylor's lyrics so that the model can work with them. Then, we create inputs for the model by iterating through Taylor's lyrics and applying the tokenization, appending each result to our list of input sequences. Then, we pad each input sequence at their start to ensure that every sequence passed into the model is exactly the same length. This is crucial to avoid matrix multiplication issues. Now, we create a set of predictors and labels from the input sequences by setting aside the last element of each sequence as a label. After this, we one-hot-encode the labels so the model can work with them more easily.

After this, we can finally create the model itself. We create a sequential model (which is what an RNN is). Next, we embed sequence indices into fixed-length vectors of length 100. After this, we create a Bidirectional LTSM (Long Short-Term Memory) layer, meaning that the layer process input in both forwards and backwards directions. An LTSM works well here because it protects against vanishing gradients and can store a lot of prior information inputted to it. Then, we create a fully connected layer which uses softmax to produce our probabilties. The loss we use is categorial cross-entropy, which is used for a lot of predictive tasks. We fit this model on the input sequences over 50 epochs so it learns the training data.

RNN Verse Generator¶

# Sampling with temperature
def sample_word(predicted, temperature = 0.7):
  predicted = np.log(predicted) / temperature
  exp_predicted = np.exp(predicted - np.max(predicted))  # Convert to probabilities
  probs = exp_predicted / np.sum(exp_predicted)  # Normalize probabilities
  sampled_index = np.random.choice(len(probs), p = probs)  # Pick a word
  return sampled_index

# Function to generate lyrics utilizing temperature scaling
def generate_lyrics(max_sequence_length, temperature = 0.7):
  generated_lyrics = ""

  for verse in range(5):  # Number of verses to generate
    for line in range(10):  # Number of lines to generate
      seed_text = random.choice(lyrics)
      prev_word = None
      line_text = ""

      for _ in range(10):  # Generate 10 additional words per line
        # Tokenize our starting word and pad it
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([seed_text])[0]
        token_list = pad_sequences([token_list], maxlen = max_sequence_length - 1, padding = 'post')
        predicted = model.predict(token_list)[0]  # Get the prediction for the next word

        # Sample from the predicted distribution with temperature scaling
        predicted_index = sample_word(predicted, temperature = temperature)

        while predicted_index == tokenizer.word_index.get(prev_word):
          # Choose another word if it's the same as the previous word
          predicted[predicted_index] = 0  # Set the probability of the previous word to 0 so it does not appear in the next sample
          predicted_index = sample_word(predicted, temperature = temperature)

        output_word = tokenizer.index_word[predicted_index] # Extract the word
        prev_word = output_word
        seed_text += " " + output_word # Add spaces between word so token has more information
        line_text += " " + output_word # Add spaces between words in output

      generated_lyrics += line_text.strip() + "\n"  # Add line to verse
    generated_lyrics += "\n"  # Add newline after each verse
  return generated_lyrics

# Generate lyrics!
# Experimented with different temperatures between 0.4 and 2, settled on 0.7
generated_lyrics = generate_lyrics(max_sequence_len, temperature = 0.7)
print(generated_lyrics)

This is how we generate verses using the RNN. We first generate a starting series randomly from Taylor’s lyrics and then tokenize it. From there, we pad it and then pass it into the model, which returns its predictions for probability distributions. Then, we sample a word from these probabilities using temperature scaling, where we divide by temperature and then normalize using exponentials to create our new rescaled probabilities, from which we then pick a word. If the word is the same as the previous word, we regenerate to prevent stagnation by setting its probability equal to 0 for that specific word generation so it will not show up. We extract the word back out of the tokenizer and concatenate it to a string. We repeat this process 10 times to create a line, we create 10 lines to make a verse, and then we create 5 verses.

Primary Analysis¶

The first metric we will use for analysis is Bilingual Evaluation Understudy, or BLEU score. BLEU was originally used for detemrining the quality of machine translation, but for NLP it allows us to compare the similarity of model-generated text to original human-generated text. As such, we will compare the samples from the Markov model and the RRN model to Taylor's original lyrics using BLEU score. BLEU works by weighted valuation of similar n-grams, which are sequences of specific words of length n. We can split both Taylor's lyrics and our generated lyrics into lists of words and then calculated BLEU using the Natural Language Toolkit.

Bilingual Evaluation Understudy (BLEU) Score for Markov Model¶

weights = (0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.1)  # Weights for uni-gram, bi-gram, tri-gram, and 4-gram
# We are weighting each n-gram progressively less, because as n increases the probability
# of an n-gram match becomes less and less

# Split baseline lyrics (Taylor swift dataset) and generated lyrics
lyrics_words = [sentence.split() for sentence in lyrics]
lines = generated_song.split('\n')
generated_words = [word for line in lines for word in line.split()]

# Calculate BLEU score utilizing our weights and a smoothing function
score = sentence_bleu(lyrics_words, generated_words, weights = weights)
print(score)

0.6831405397525627

0.2646917307369639

BLEU scores are always between 0 and 1, with a score closer to 1 meaning the generated text corresponds more closely to the original training data, and a score closer to 0 meaning the generated text does not correspond very closely to the original. The Markov model has a score of 0.68, which means that it is fairly close to the original training data and is performing well. The RNN model has a less good score of 0.26, but considering that it is a more general-purpose model compared to the training data it makes sense that it would not fit as closely to the training data.

Sentiment Analysis¶

Here, we also analyze the sentiments of our lyrics dataset with the lyrics generated by our models. The sentiments were generated by using the Vader sentiment analyzer provided by NLTK. Vader is a rules-based analyzer commonly used for social media and business sentiment analysis. We chose it because it was the simplest to use by far while still providing fairly accurate results. In this case, we use Vader to generate polarity scores, which roughly represent the valence or intentisty of the text it is analyzing. It is somewhat analogous to the valence score given to Taylor Swift's songs by Spotify, although this is purely based on lyrics. From those scores, we attach a label to the lyric based on whether the score is above, below, or equal to zero. The results of random samples of Taylor's lyrics is compared to randomly generated verses of the Markov Model and RNN are shown in the grouped bar chart above. We found that while our Markov model refelcts negativity in Taylor's lyrics well, it overly favors positive sentiment while Taylor tends to be more neutral.

In [ ]:
class SentimentAnalyzer():
  def __init__(self, lyrics, title):
    # NLTK initialization
    self.lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    self.analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

    # preprocessing and analysis
    self.tokens = self.preprocess_lyrics(lyrics)
    self.sent_counts = {}
    self.sentiments = self.get_sentiments(self.tokens)

    self.title = title

  def preprocess_lyrics(self, lyrics):
    processed_lyrics = []
    for lyric in lyrics:
      # tokenization
      tokens = word_tokenize(lyric.lower())
      # removing stop words ("the", "is", "a", etc.)
      filtered_tokens = [token for token in tokens if token not in stopwords.words('english')]
      # lemmatization (grouping together word variations like "stop" and "stopping")
      lemmatized_tokens = [self.lemmatizer.lemmatize(token) for token in filtered_tokens]
      processed_lyrics.append(' '.join(lemmatized_tokens))
    return processed_lyrics

  def get_sentiments(self, lyrics):
    sentiments = []
    for lyric in lyrics:
      # get the valence of a line from intensity analyzer
      score = self.analyzer.polarity_scores(lyric)
      # group scores into positive, negative, and neutral sentiment
      if score['compound'] > 0:
        sentiment = "positive"
      elif score['compound'] < 0:
        sentiment = "negative"
      else:
        sentiment = "neutral"
      sentiments.append(sentiment)

    # count number of positives, negatives, neutrals in data
    self.sent_counts["pos"] = reduce(lambda acc, x: acc + 1 if x == "positive" else acc, sentiments, 0)
    self.sent_counts["neg"] = reduce(lambda acc, x: acc + 1 if x == "negative" else acc, sentiments, 0)
    self.sent_counts["neut"] = reduce(lambda acc, x: acc + 1 if x == "neutral" else acc, sentiments, 0)

    return sentiments

  # singular bar chart visualization for
  def visualize(self):
    plt.bar(["Positive", "Neutral", "Negative"], [self.sent_counts["pos"], self.sent_counts["neut"], self.sent_counts["neg"]], color=['green', 'red', 'blue'])
    plt.xlabel('Sentiments')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title(f'Sentiment Analysis of {self.title}')
    plt.show()

  @staticmethod
  # compares counts of sentiment for two sets of lyrics
  def group_visualize(analyzer1, analyzer2, analyzer3):
    # Create subplots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))

    # Data for each analyzer
    analyzers = [(analyzer1, axes[0]), (analyzer2, axes[1]), (analyzer3, axes[2])]

    for analyzer, ax in analyzers:
        counts = [analyzer.sent_counts["pos"], analyzer.sent_counts["neut"], analyzer.sent_counts["neg"]]
        X = ["Positive", "Neutral", "Negative"]
        X_axis = np.arange(3)

        # Plot bar graph
        ax.bar(X_axis, counts, label=analyzer.title)
        ax.set_xticks(X_axis)
        ax.set_xticklabels(X)
        ax.set_xlabel("Groups")
        ax.set_ylabel("Number of Words")
        ax.set_title(f"Number of Words in each Sentiment Group ({analyzer.title})")
        ax.legend()

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Sentinment analysis is the the process of analyzing text to determine whether its emotional tone is positive, negative, or neutral. We ran sentiment analysis on the original text, the generated text from the Markov Model, and the generated text from the RNN. From the bar graphs, we can see that the original lyrics and the Markov Model generated lyrics split the words into the three categories relatively similarly. However, the RNN model classifies most of the words as neutral. This suggests that the RNN model is not that good at capturing sentiment.

# Count word frequency
def word_freq(text):
  word_freq = {}
  words = text.split()

  for word in words:
    # Filter out stopwords
    if word.lower() not in stop_words:
      word_freq[word] = word_freq.get(word, 0) + 1
  return word_freq

# Sort and retrive top n words
def top_words(word_freq, n):
  sorted_word_freq = sorted(word_freq.items(), key = lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)
  return dict(sorted_word_freq[:n])

Insights and Conclusions¶

Our initial goal with this project was to recreate songs in the style of Taylor Swift using machine learning models for text generation. We wanted to explore different types of models to perform this task, so we made a Markov chain model and a recurrent neural network (RNN). To evaluate how well our models performed, we calculated BLEU score and performed sentiment analysis to see how well the emotion of Taylor's original lyrics transferred over to the generated lyrics. We also made some wordclouds and bar graphs to display the frequency of words in both original lyrics and generated to see if the main ideas were coming across.

Overall, we can draw some interesting conclusions from this experiment. The Markov model seemed to show conclusively that it is possible to recreate the general style of Taylor’s lyrics probabilistically. The model was not perfect and often did not directly recreate language semantics, but the BLEU score of 0.68 and relatively coherent sentence structure shows us that it could recreate Taylor’s vibe pretty convincingly. Furthermore, it had a similar ratio of sentiments (positive, neutral, and negative) to Taylor’s original lyrics. A lot of the top words were very similar to the original lyrics, such as "love" and "think", as they showed up frequently in both the original lyrics and the Markov-generated lyrics. Meanwhile, the RNN model was not as good at doing so, as it tended to miss semantics and pair a lot of words together that created nonsense combinations. The BLEU score of 0.26 was relatively poor as well. Interestingly, it seemed to produce a much higher ratio of neutral words and fewer positive and negative words than the Markov model, which suggests that it was not as good at capturing sentiment, either. The top words were not as close of a match as the Markov model's lyrics provided. However, the one upside it does have over the Markov model is that the Markov model is pretty tied to the training data, so it cannot really be applied effectively to any other data. The RNN model, on the other hand, can absolutely be tested on any other input dataset pretty easily, and will be far more generalizable. In the future, we hope to explore more complex and layered RNNs to see if we can improve the quality of our generation.
